post_text:
Information & COVID Protocols for VB @ Southwest on Thursday.

Admission will be $5.00 for adults, $4.00 for students. We will have two gates, one for home fans and one for visiting fans. Both will be located in the commons area outside the gym. ALL FANS MUST BE MASKED TO ENTER THE FACILITY.

Concessions will be available in the high school gymnasium after 5:00 PM. Concessions will be limited (Drink, Candy, Hot Dog, Popcorn). Anyone purchasing from the concession stand should be masked.

Sutherland will have fans access on the East side of our gym. Southern Valley will have the West side, South end. Southwest will have the West side North end. Cheerleaders are allowed but should mask up in all areas of the building when not actively involved in cheering.

Football: 75% Capacity = 315 in attendance

Away spectators will social distance according to family groups and in groups of no larger than 8

Away spectators will sit on the West side of the football field

post_text:
Perkins County Activities Covid Protocols

If you are ill or have COVID-19, flu-like symptoms, please stay home.

Masks are optional, please adhere to social distancing guidelines and suggestions.

Ticket takers will wear masks or face shields.

There will be only one concession stand. Workers will wear masks. Those handling money will not serve food or drinks.

Opposing fans will occupy the north bleachers. Perkins County fans will occupy the south bleachers.

Attendance will not exceed 75% capacity (723 occupants).

Perkins County student section will remain in the northwest bleachers. However, when entering and exiting the gym and bleacher section, they will enter and exit to the west gym wall and proceed past the north (home team) bleachers.

As of August 25, 2020

post_text: The last few months have been a true reflection of TEAMWORK and today was no exception. There has been a tremendous amount of planning and preparing to ensure the safety of our students and staff at Sutherland Public School and everyone has been involved....teachers, custodians, nurse, secretaries, admin. We are incredibly proud of our students today as they accepted the changes placed before them and respectfully wore their masks throughout the day. We know this wasn’t east and probably not preferred by most. Teachers provided many opportunities for “mask” breaks which will be essential throughout this time. We are ALL in this TOGETHER and with patience, flexibility, and grace we will make this a great year for all. It will be different, but all we have to do is find the good in the “different” for now. So grateful we were TOGETHER as a SAILOR family today!

We are excited to have students coming to school tomorrow for the 2020-2021 school year. We want to share a few reminders:

*Adults & students, please wear your mask outside while waiting to enter the building.
*Social distance while waiting to enter the building.
*The doors will open at 7:30 for breakfast and 7:45 for everyone else.
*When you enter the building an adult will help you with hand sanitizer (placed at both entrances to the building).
*You will walk directly to your homeroom class.
*Adults will be available to help all new students find their classroom.

We are ALL in this TOGETHER and can't wait to see you tomorrow!

The 2020 Firecracker Run is going virtual!

Participants should go to www.platteriverfitness.com .

Click on Events and Results then click on the Firecracker race and register being sure to choose a distance. Be sure to choose the $5 mailing upgrade if you want your race swag mailed. Please choose the $2 upgrade for 2 XL and 3 XL. To keep in the spirit of race day, the "official" race day is July 4th, but participants can continue to register and turn in their race time and distance toplatteriverfitness@gmail.com through July 31. The first 125 to register are guaranteed a medal. The pickup dates will be August 10th and 11th from 5-6 at Eakes Office Solutions 520 N Vine St. North Platte and the mailout date will be August 10th. I will deliver to those living within city limits in Sutherland. There are paper forms at the Rec Center in North Platte for those who are more comfortable the old-fashioned way! Please contact Teresa Hafer at 308-386-6462 with any questions.

post_text:
Several students from Sutherland Public School were among the nearly 160,000 students worldwide to participate this year in the Math Olympiad program. Sutherland Elementary had 19 students in 4th-6th grades who qualified to participate in the program based on their performance on their NWEA MAP and NSCAS tests. Students included: Vivienne J., Bryden R., Teagan F., Keigan K., Dillon F., Morgan K., Macradee L., Easton D., Marshall P., Max B., Zoe B., Maleah V., Hayli J., Kale M., Addisyn G., Jali M., Izzy B., Jackson S. and JT L.. They participated in a series of five monthly contests of 5 problems each, from November to March, and weekly practice sessions under the supervision and coaching of Mrs. Jewell Samuelson. She taught the students to solve unusual and difficult problems and to think creatively. Congratulations to all of our students for their hard work as “MATHletes”!

Jackson S. was awarded the team trophy, Math Olympiad patch, and silver pin for being in the top 10%.

Sutherland Public School is looking for a part-time piano accompanist to support the 7-12 choral music program. Rehearsals run from 10:30-12 each day and two mornings before school from 7-7:45. The accompanist would play for JH/HS concert choir and show choirs, as well as play for solos and small groups for contests for choir and possibly band in the spring.

Position will be for the 2020-2021 school year. Please submit a resume and letter of interest to: Dustin Mitchell, 401 Walnut Street, Sutherland, NE 69165

This position is subject to veterans preference.

Congratulations to the 6th Grade Presidential Award recipients for 2019-2020. Students receiving the Presidential Award for Educational Excellence had a 90% GPA for the Fall semester and 85% on Reading or Math NWEA MAP tests or 2 teacher recommendations.

Students receiving the Presidential Award for Educational Achievement achieved high scores or showed outstanding growth, improvement, commitment or intellectual development in particular subjects, such as English, Math, Social Studies, and Science. This award is meant to recognize students who work hard and give their best effort in school.

Way to go 6th graders! We are proud of your academic achievements during the 2019-2020 school year.

shared_text:
Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
May 8 at 2:08 AM ·

Our next featured senior is Bonnie Naughtin. Bonnie shows her versatility and talent in the fact that over her four years of speech she has competed in four of the nine events, making it to state in three of them. It most likely would have been all four if her season had not ended early. Bonnie was also another member of the OID that has been together since they were freshmen (which will be featured in tomorrow's post).

Bonnie also uses her talents for the benefit of the team as a whole. She not only wrote her own poetry this year, but she also wrote Serious Prose scripts for Emma Wareham and Abbie Morris. And although this spotlight is focused on speech, I feel it is important to note that she also composed and recorded all of the music for the one act play for the last two years.

In addition to her OID, Bonnie was incredibly successful with her Poetry program this year. She brought many an audience to tears with her heartfelt look at the struggles of dementia.

Thank you so much for your hard work over the years, Bonnie. We can't wait to see what you do next!

Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
May 3 at 10:49 PM ·

It's graduation week, and that means it's time to put a spotlight on our seniors!

The first senior we would like to honor is Megan Coffman. This was her first year at the school and her first year on the team, and we are so glad that she joined us. Megan participated in two events this year. The first event she picked up was a hilarious OID called "Elf on a Shelf Must Die" with Dominic Ralston, Taylor Weber, Taarna Gray, and Trinity Turner. Wanting to further challenge herself and expand her horizons, she also put together an informative speech about tabletop gaming. Although her season ended before districts, we would like to honor Megan by sharing one of her OID performances. Enjoy!

Thank you for a fantastic season, Megan. Good luck as you move on to your next chapter.

And thank you to Stage Partners for permission to post this performance.

shared_text:
Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
May 1 at 8:50 PM ·

To finish out our group of sophomores, we have the talented Maverick Naughtin. Maverick qualified for the district team in two very different events. He joined a hilarious OID with four seniors (which will be featured in a future post), and he also qualified in the much more serious event called Extemp. Extemp is a unique and demanding event where you have an hour to write your speech on a current events topic that you draw right then. And you have to do this up to three separate times if you make finals! Add in another event where you are coordinating schedules with four other people and that makes for a very busy day! Maverick has always thrived under this pressure, consistently medaling in both events. Maverick was a state qualifier in two events last year, and was hoping to repeat that feat before his season was cut short.

Thank you for your hard work this year Maverick! We can't wait to see what your future holds!

Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
April 29 at 8:14 AM ·

Today we are featuring the talented Mekenna Fisher. It would be difficult to find a harder worker than this young lady. When you are regularly getting medals and even winning your event, it would be easy to coast on that success, but Mekenna is always striving to improve. She takes the time to come in and go over tab sheets, ask questions, practice, and find ways to keep getting better and better every single week. This hard work resulted in the accomplishment of medaling in three events in the same meet- Two 1st place and one 2nd!

Mekenna was set to compete in Entertainment and Extemp at districts for a shot at state before her season was cut short. The attached video is Mekenna's entertainment speech about how to find the perfect boyfriend.

Thank you for all of your hard work this season, Mekenna. We can't wait to see what you do next!

Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
April 27 at 8:10 PM ·

For today's feature we have a hardworking pair of young ladies who put together a hilarious duet about a pushy beauty pageant mom and her reluctant daughter.

Duet is not an easy event as it is the only one that you are not allowed to have a script at all, meaning you have to have it all memorized from the very first meet. Despite being busy is many other activities, Faith Stewart and Kellan Copeland found the time to practice together and earn themselves a spot on the district team.

Thank you so much for all of your hard work this year Faith and Kellan! We can't wait to see what you do next!

Unfortunately we have been unable to obtain publisher permission to post the video of their performance at this time, but we will update this post if that changes!

Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
April 26 at 9:14 PM ·

Last school year, several people came to me to tell me about a new student who blew everybody away with her speaking skills at the FFA Greenhand ceremony. Rumor had it that she was going to be a great addition to the speech team. How right they were! For the last two years, Paige Hoelting has been an amazing addition to the speech team, and we are so glad to have her!

Not only was she part of our amazing trio of Extempers who must each draw their topic on a current event, write their speech in under and hour and then perform it (repeating this process for each round), but participated with an informative speech as well. It is this speech that she was planning to perform at districts for a shot at state.

Thank you for your hard work this season, Paige! We are so glad to have you on the team!

Sutherland Public School Speech and One Act
April 24 at 8:44 PM ·

Our next feature is a group of five hardworking young women. After the last day of finals in December when most students had cleared the school to start their winter break, these girls stayed several hours longer to get help picking out a script so that they could practice over break. Olivia Miller, Serena Martinez, Cloee Peterson, McKenna Bliss, and Bailey Zona worked hard over break and throughout the rest of the season to put together a performance which not only earned them medals and a spot on the district team, but took on the difficult and intense topic of bullying in schools.

Thank you for a fantastic season, girls. I can't wait to see what you do next!

Also, a big thank you Stage Partners for permission to post this performance.

This week was scheduled to be a week of Early Childhood at Sutherland Public School with a kickoff for our Smart Start Sailors initiative (birth to school age....more information to come on this), Little Sailors Preschool Orientation, Junior Kindergarten Orientation, and Kindergarten Round-Up which is always a very exciting time for all of us.

Information packets for students registered for Little Sailors Preschool, Junior Kindergarten, and Kindergarten, with all necessary forms, will be available at the school for parents on April 29th. Please stop by to pick up your child's packet.

Just a reminder that students going into Junior Kindergarten and Kindergarten are required to have a vision exam, a physical, and have required immunizations that need to be completed prior to starting school. If you have any questions in regard to the requirements, please contact Mrs. Floyd at the school.

text: Elementary Parents: New lessons and materials can be picked up on April 29th from 8:00-3:30. More information on the school Facebook page.

post_text:
Sutherland Elementary Parents: We will have learning materials for you to pick up on Wednesday, April 29th from 8:00-3:30 at the front doors of the school. The materials you pick up on April 29th will be what they need for lessons through May 15th, which will be the last day for student remote learning. This will also be an opportunity to turn in any work that your child has completed and return library books or library books from your child's classroom teacher.

May 18th & 19th will be used for students to return all textbooks, school materials, and receive any end of the year things from their teacher and also any of their belongings that have still been at school. More detailed information will be shared closer to these dates.

Thank you for your patience and grace during this time of remote learning. I am extremely proud of our students, parents, teachers, and community. Continue to do your schoolwork and find a blessing in each day. This has been a tremendous challenge, but we are #SAILORSTRONG and we are #STRONGERTOGETHER!

May 18th & 19th will be used for students to return all textbooks, school materials, and receive any end of the year things from their teacher and also any of their belongings that have still been at school. More detailed information will be shared closer to these dates.

Thank you for your patience and grace during this time of remote learning. I am extremely proud of our students, parents, teachers, and community. Continue to do your schoolwork and find a blessing in each day. This has been a tremendous challenge, but we are #SAILORSTRONG and we are #STRONGERTOGETHER!

Hey Sailors! I am missing you so much and wanted to share our Principal Read Aloud for April with you. The book is Scribble Stones by Diane Alber. If you really enjoy the book and want a copy of your own, you can find it on Amazon (https://tinyurl.com/y9hfsl4v).

After listening to the book Scribble Stones, find a rock of your own. Using paint, crayons, markers, stickers, yarn...anything!...create your own scribble stone. Take a picture of you and your stone in a well-lit space (outside is great!) Post your photo on this link! Hope you enjoy the story!

post_text:
Our Sailor teachers have worked so hard all week to prepare materials both in paper and electronic form for our PreK-6 students during this extraordinary time with COVID-19! Check out the before and after pictures from today (3/20/2020).

Our parents are completely awesome and want what is best for their children. All materials have been picked up and ready to put a new twist on learning!

Thank you to our custodians for setting up the commons area. Thank you to our teachers and secretaries who helped get materials to our parents in a safe manner today. You are all the best.

We do want to remind parents to email admin or teachers with any questions during this time. We are all learning as we go. #SailorPride

post_text: The Sutherland 7th Grade class will be selling Coca-Cola products (Soft drinks, Dasani Water, Lemonade, Powerade, Body Armor, Gold Peak Ice Tea). March 9th through March 20th. Please watch for students with order forms, or contact Mr. Mraz at the school to place an order. Please make checks payable to Sutherland Public Schools. Delivery date will be April 2nd at Sutherland Public School. Please return your shell carrying container to your nearest grocery store or to the school to avoid the fundraising group being assessed a fee.

The Sutherland Music Department is kicking off their Little Caesars Pizza Kit Fundraiser this week. Please watch for music students with order forms, or order online. To order online, please click the link to go to Pizza Kit Fundraising Page. You will need to enter our fundraiser ID# 382558. All online orders must be paid by credit card. All orders must be submitted by March 8, 2020. All pizza kits will be delivered to the school, unless you select a different delivery method and pay shipping. Deliveries to the school will be made the week of March 23. Please check for the delivery date updates on Facebook.

https://www.pizzakit.com/LoginCreate.aspx?returnto=%2ffundraising-products%3fshop%3d1%26f%3d382558%26s%3d151738
